CommonFields.Title: Preparation and properties of poly(methylmethacrylate)–silica hybrid materials incorporating reactive silica nanoparticles
Author: Sugimoto, Hideki
Daimatsu, Kazuki
Nakanishi, Eiji
Ogasawara, Yutaka
Yasumura, Takashi
Inomata, Katsuhiro
CommonFields.Location: Graduate School of Engineering, Nagoya Institute of Technology, Gokiso-cho, Showa-ku, Nagoya 466-8555, Japan

Mixing.Description: To introduce methacryloyl groups onto colloidal silica surfaces, a given amount of MOI and di-n-butyltin dilaurate (DBTL) (ca. 250–500 ppm) catalyst were added to EAc-ST, and the reaction was carried out at room temperature for 24 h with stirring.

Drying-Evaporation.Description: To obtain a colloidal silica/MMA dispersion (MMA–silica), ethyl acetate was first removed from the mixed solution with a rotary evaporator.

Mixing.Description: To prepare PMMA–silica hybrid copolymers, MMA was added to the MOI/colloidal silica dispersion described above. The copolymerization used benzoyl peroxide (BPO) as a free radical initiator, was carried out at 80°C for 24 h.

Transmission_Electron_Microscopy.Description: The sample (thickness: 80 nm) was prepared for TEM with a microtome knife.

Fourier_Transform_Infrared_Spectroscopy.Description: Used to characterize the reactive silica nanoparticles

Thermogravimetric_Analysis.Description: TGA was carried out over the range 25–600°C with a platinum pan, at a heating rate of 10°C/min. Alumina powder was used as a reference material.

Nuclear_Magnetic_Resonance.Equipment: Bruker model AVANCE 200 FT NMR spectrometer
Nuclear_Magnetic_Resonance.Description: Used to characterize the reactive silica nanoparticles
